  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Community perceptions of the ACE Africa program: acceptability, participation, ownership and sustainability</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In some of the remote rural areas of Kenya, people lack access to basic services including medication, nutritious food, shelter, psychosocial support and education. There are a large number of adults showing with symptoms of HIV and an equally large number of orphans and vulnerable children. The project will work with over 500 community volunteers and continue to strengthen community structures to build their skills to care for vulnerable children and people with HIV. Training will be provided in proposal writing and budgeting, project management and implementation, nutrition-based income generating activities and HIV counselling and testing. ACE will also provide support to strengthen work place policies for HIV and AIDS, and to engage government, community and other partners in the protection and the promotion of human rights and child welfare at both local and national level. The project will result in improved community health and economic status, increased protection and advocacy for the rights of women and children, and reduced stigma associated with HIV and AIDS. It will also help to strengthen a community-led orphan support system involving government and local partners.</narrative>
  </description>
